                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d483">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">701.5211/517</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Chief of the Division of Protocol and
                        Conferences</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Southgate</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-10-10">October 10,
                            1936</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>At the conclusion of his conversation with the Spanish Ambassador<note n="80"
                        xml:id="d483fn80">See <hi rend="italic">supra.</hi>
                    </note> the Secretary referred to the conversation recently held between Mr.
                    Dunn and Mr. de la Casa with reference to a speech made by Mr. Gibernau of the
                    Spanish Embassy. The Secretary stated that <pb facs="0638" n="539"
                        xml:id="pg_539"/> apparently what Mr. Dunn had said had been misunderstood
                    and that there was no intention whatsoever on the part of the Department to make
                    any statement which could be construed as restricting the freedom of speech of
                    members of foreign Missions on subjects of general interest concerning their own
                    countries.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
